Image compression using PCA¶

Objectives:

  • Use a high-dimensional photo.
  • Print the original photo.
  • Reduce this photo's size to smaller dimension.
  • Print size-by-size resulted photo and the original one.

Note in this notebook:

  • #: comment command lines, you can uncomment to run them.
  • ##: describe of a command line, you can't run this.
  • ###: title of a block of related commmands.

fname = fdir + 'labrador.jpg'

imgGD = np.asarray(Image.open(fname).convert("L"))
## If you have an L mode image, that means it is a single channel image - normally 
##   interpreted as greyscale. The L means that is just stores the Luminance. 
##   It is very compact, but only stores a greyscale, not colour.

plt.imshow(imgGD, cmap='gray', vmin=0, vmax=255)
plt.show()
print(img.shape)

(768, 1024)

Apply PCA¶

In [18]:
pca = PCA(n_components=100, svd_solver='full')
pca.fit(img)

nd = pca.transform(img) # transform to 100 dim (768x100)
ni = pca.inverse_transform(nd) # transform back to 768x1024
plt.imshow(ni, cmap=plt.cm.gray)

# plt.savefig(fdir + 'face_bw_compress.jpg')
plt.show() # has to come after .savefig()!!!

## fix warning "Lossy conversion from float64 to uint8. Range [-15.551662973532302, 265.94514632224184]. Convert image to uint8 prior to saving to suppress this warning."
ni_uint8 = ni.astype(np.uint8) # only for imageio.imwrite()

imageio.imwrite(fdir + 'face_bw_compress.jpg', ni_uint8)
print("nd.shape: ", np.shape(nd))
print("ni.shape: ", ni.shape)
print("variance retained: ", round(np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)[-1]*100), '%')

nd.shape:  (768, 100)
ni.shape:  (768, 1024)
variance retained:  96.0 %

Comment: We only use 100 components but we can retain 96% variances!

Colored images¶

Remark: Different from grayscale images (2 dimensions), full colored images have 3rd dimension (RGB) [ref].

In [51]:
## USING SCIPY
img = misc.face()
plt.axis('off') # don't show axes
plt.imshow(img)
plt.show()
print("Img's shape: ", img.shape)
imageio.imwrite(fdir + 'face.jpg', img)
print("Original image's size: ", round((os.stat(fdir + 'face.jpg').st_size)/1024), "KB")

img's shape:  (768, 1024, 3)
Original image's size:  144 KB

The array has 768 rows each of pixel 1024x3 = 3072. Let's reshape it into a format that PCA can understand.

In [52]:
img_r = np.reshape(img, (768, 3072)) 
print(img_r.shape)

(768, 3072)

It's time to apply PCA.

In [72]:
## apply pca with 100 components
cpca = PCA(n_components=100, svd_solver='full').fit(img_r)
img_c = cpca.transform(img_r)
print("img_c's shape: ", img_c.shape)
print("variance retained: ", round(np.cumsum(cpca.explained_variance_ratio_)[-1]*100), '%')

img_c's shape:  (768, 100)
variance retained:  96.0 %

Back to 768x1024x3,

In [73]:
img_iv = cpca.inverse_transform(img_c)
print("inversed image's shape: ", img_iv.shape)

inversed image's shape:  (768, 3072)
In [74]:
## reshape to 768x1024x3
img_iv = np.reshape(img_iv, (768,1024,3))
print("after reshaping: ", img_iv.shape)

after reshaping:  (768, 1024, 3)
In [81]:
## plot
plt.axis('off')
## we use 'astype' for warning "Clipping input data to the valid range for imshow with RGB data ([0..1] for floats or [0..255] for integers)"
img_iv_uint8 = img_iv.astype('uint8')
plt.imshow(img_iv_uint8)
print("Compressed img's shape: ", img_iv_uint8.shape)

Compressed img's shape:  (768, 1024, 3)
In [0]:
imageio.imwrite(fdir + 'face_compressed.jpg', img_iv_uint8)
